m</i> ‘palm tree’ + the suffix <i>-ér</i> (a derivative of Latin <i>-erius</i>) or <i>-er</i> (from German)."],"variants":[{"name":"Milford","meanings":["English (mainly Devon): habitational name from any of the many places called Milford, deriving from Old English <i>myln</i> ‘mill’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","Irish (Antrim and Galway): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maolfhoghmhair</b> ‘descendant of <i>Maolgfhoghmhair</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘chief of harvest’. The Irish name was first Anglicized as <b>Mullover</b>, which was later assimilated to <i>Milford</i>. See also   Palmer  ."]},{"name":"Palmiere","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Dante, Enrico, Nicola, Salvatore, Vittorio.","Italian: from <i>palmiere</i> ‘palmer, pilgrim’. See   Palmer  ."]},{"name":"Parmer","meanings":["English: variant of   Palmer  .","Indian (northern states): variant of   Parmar  ."]},{"name":"Palmore","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Palmer   or an Americanized form of South German   Balmer  ."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":7,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime